definition---Uninitialized pointers are called as wild pointers in C which points to arbitrary (random) memory location. This wild pointer may lead a program to 
             behave wrongly or to crash.












-------------------------------------------------------------Example programm for wild pointer----------------------------------------------------------------------------

#include<stdio.h>
int main()
{
    int *ptr;
    printf("ptr=%d\n",*ptr);
    return 0;
}
